import pandas as pd
import tensorflow as tf
import tensorflow_hub as hub
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, Dense
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model

# Load BERT layer from TensorFlow Hub
bert_layer = hub.KerasLayer("https://tfhub.dev/google/universal-sentence-encoder/4", trainable=False)

    
 
 

        

          
 

          

            
 

          

        

      

    

      

        

          
          

            
          

        

      
import autokeras as ak
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

# Load dataset
data = pd.read_csv('/content/Sample_dataset_for training.csv')

    
 
 

        

          

          

            
 

          

        

      

    

      

        

          
          

            
          

        

      

# Check for any missing values and fill as necessary
data['Tokenized_Resume'] = data['Tokenized_Resume'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Description'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Description'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Title'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Title'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Skills'] = data['Tokenized_Skills'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Experience'] = data['Experience'].fillna(0)  # Fill numeric column with 0 if there are missing values
data['Resume_Score'] = data['Resume_Score'].fillna(data['Resume_Score'].mean())  # Replace NaN in target with mean

# Combine primary text fields for embeddings
X_main_text = data['Tokenized_Resume'] + " " + data['Tokenized_Job_Description']
X_additional_text_1 = data['Tokenized_Job_Title']
X_additional_text_2 = data['Tokenized_Skills']
y = data['Resume_Score'].to_numpy()  # Convert target to numpy array

# Extract and scale the numeric column
X_numeric = data[['Experience']]
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_numeric_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_numeric)

# Split data
X_train_main_text, X_test_main_text, X_train_text1, X_test_text1, X_train_text2, X_test_text2, X_train_num, X_test_num, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_main_text, X_additional_text_1, X_additional_text_2, X_numeric_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42
)

# Function to convert text to BERT embeddings and output as numpy arrays
def embed_text(texts):
    embeddings = bert_layer(tf.convert_to_tensor(texts))
    return embeddings.numpy()  # Convert to numpy array

# Embed train and test text data and convert to numpy arrays
X_train_main_embedded = embed_text(X_train_main_text.tolist())
X_test_main_embedded = embed_text(X_test_main_text.tolist())
X_train_text1_embedded = embed_text(X_train_text1.tolist())
X_test_text1_embedded = embed_text(X_test_text1.tolist())
X_train_text2_embedded = embed_text(X_train_text2.tolist())
X_test_text2_embedded = embed_text(X_test_text2.tolist())

# Define AutoKeras model with multiple text inputs and one numeric input
input_main_text = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_main_embedded.shape[1],), name='main_text_input')
input_text1 = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_text1_embedded.shape[1],), name='additional_text_input1')
input_text2 = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_text2_embedded.shape[1],), name='additional_text_input2')
input_numeric = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_input')

# Combine inputs and add regression head
merged = ak.Merge()([input_main_text, input_text1, input_text2, input_numeric])
output = ak.RegressionHead()(merged)

# Set up AutoKeras AutoModel
model = ak.AutoModel(
    inputs=[input_main_text, input_text1, input_text2, input_numeric],
    outputs=output,
    overwrite=True,
    max_trials=10  # Adjust for more model searches if needed
)

# Prepare inputs as dictionaries for AutoKeras
X_train_dict = {
    'main_text_input': X_train_main_embedded,
    'additional_text_input1': X_train_text1_embedded,
    'additional_text_input2': X_train_text2_embedded,
    'numeric_input': X_train_num
}

X_test_dict = {
    'main_text_input': X_test_main_embedded,
    'additional_text_input1': X_test_text1_embedded,
    'additional_text_input2': X_test_text2_embedded,
    'numeric_input': X_test_num
}

# Train the AutoKeras model
model.fit(X_train_dict, y_train, epochs=10, validation_split=0.1)

# Predict and calculate R^2
y_pred = model.predict(X_test_dict).flatten()
r2_autokeras = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
print("AutoKeras Model with Multiple Text Inputs and Numeric Feature R^2 Score:", r2_autokeras)

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import tensorflow as tf
import tensorflow_hub as hub
import autokeras as ak
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

# Load BERT layer for text embedding
bert_layer = hub.KerasLayer("https://tfhub.dev/google/universal-sentence-encoder/4", trainable=False)

# Load dataset
data = pd.read_csv('/content/Sample_dataset_for training.csv')

# Fill missing values
data['Tokenized_Resume'] = data['Tokenized_Resume'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Description'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Description'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Title'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Title'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Skills'] = data['Tokenized_Skills'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Experience'] = data['Experience'].fillna(0)

# Enhanced feature engineering: similarity and match scores
tfidf_vectorizer = TfidfVectorizer()
job_desc_tfidf = tfidf_vectorizer.fit_transform(data['Tokenized_Job_Description'])
resume_tfidf = tfidf_vectorizer.transform(data['Tokenized_Resume'])
cosine_similarities = [cosine_similarity(job_desc_tfidf[i], resume_tfidf[i])[0, 0] for i in range(job_desc_tfidf.shape[0])]

data['cosine_similarity'] = cosine_similarities

def calculate_overlap(list1, list2):
    set1 = set(list1.lower().replace('[', '').replace(']', '').replace("'", "").split(", "))
    set2 = set(list2.lower().replace('[', '').replace(']', '').replace("'", "").split(", "))
    return len(set1.intersection(set2)) / (len(set1) + len(set2))

data['skill_match_score'] = data.apply(lambda row: calculate_overlap(row['Tokenized_Skills'], row['Tokenized_Job_Description']), axis=1)
data['job_title_match_score'] = data.apply(lambda row: calculate_overlap(row['Tokenized_Job_Title'], row['Tokenized_Resume']), axis=1)

# Extract main features and target
X_main_text = data['Tokenized_Resume'] + " " + data['Tokenized_Job_Description']
X_numeric = data[['Experience', 'cosine_similarity', 'skill_match_score', 'job_title_match_score']]
y = data['Resume_Score'].fillna(data['Resume_Score'].mean()).to_numpy()

# Scale numeric features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_numeric_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_numeric)

# Split data
X_train_text, X_test_text, X_train_num, X_test_num, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_main_text, X_numeric_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42
)

# Convert text data to BERT embeddings and output as numpy arrays
def embed_text(texts):
    embeddings = bert_layer(tf.convert_to_tensor(texts))
    return embeddings.numpy()  # Convert to numpy array

X_train_text_embedded = embed_text(X_train_text.tolist())
X_test_text_embedded = embed_text(X_test_text.tolist())

# Verify that embeddings and numeric data are numpy arrays and have correct shapes
print("X_train_text_embedded shape:", X_train_text_embedded.shape)
print("X_train_num shape:", X_train_num.shape)
print("y_train shape:", y_train.shape)

# Check for NaN or inf values in the inputs
assert not np.isnan(X_train_text_embedded).any(), "NaN values found in text embeddings"
assert not np.isinf(X_train_text_embedded).any(), "Inf values found in text embeddings"
assert not np.isnan(X_train_num).any(), "NaN values found in numeric inputs"
assert not np.isinf(X_train_num).any(), "Inf values found in numeric inputs"

# Start with a simpler model (only numeric input) to ensure data compatibility
input_numeric = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_input')
output = ak.RegressionHead()(input_numeric)
model = ak.AutoModel(inputs=input_numeric, outputs=output, overwrite=True, max_trials=5)

import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, Dense, Concatenate, Dropout
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score

# Define input layers
input_text = Input(shape=(X_train_text_embedded.shape[1],), name='text_input')
input_numeric = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_input')

# Text embedding branch
text_branch = Dense(256, activation='relu')(input_text)
text_branch = Dropout(0.5)(text_branch)

# Numeric branch
numeric_branch = Dense(64, activation='relu')(input_numeric)
numeric_branch = Dropout(0.5)(numeric_branch)

# Combine branches
combined = Concatenate()([text_branch, numeric_branch])
combined = Dense(128, activation='relu')(combined)
combined = Dropout(0.3)(combined)
output = Dense(1)(combined)

# Define model
model = Model(inputs=[input_text, input_numeric], outputs=output)
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.RootMeanSquaredError(name="rmse")])

# Train model
history = model.fit([X_train_text_embedded, X_train_num], y_train, epochs=20, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.1)

# Predict and calculate R^2
y_pred = model.predict([X_test_text_embedded, X_test_num]).flatten()
r2_score_custom_model = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
print("Custom Model with Enhanced Features R^2 Score:", r2_score_custom_model)

# Step 1: Define and Train the Neural Network Model
def create_neural_network(learning_rate=0.0005, text_units=256, numeric_units=128, combined_units=128, dropout_rate=0.4, l2_reg=0.001):
    input_text = Input(shape=(X_train_text_embedded.shape[1],), name='text_input')
    text_branch = Dense(text_units, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(l2_reg))(input_text)
    text_branch = BatchNormalization()(text_branch)
    text_branch = Dropout(dropout_rate)(text_branch)

    input_numeric = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_input')
    numeric_branch = Dense(numeric_units, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(l2_reg))(input_numeric)
    numeric_branch = BatchNormalization()(numeric_branch)
    numeric_branch = Dropout(dropout_rate)(numeric_branch)

    combined = Concatenate()([text_branch, numeric_branch])
    combined = Dense(combined_units, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(l2_reg))(combined)
    combined = BatchNormalization()(combined)
    combined = Dropout(dropout_rate)(combined)
    output = Dense(1)(combined)

    model = Model(inputs=[input_text, input_numeric], outputs=output)
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate), loss='mse', metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.RootMeanSquaredError(name="rmse")])
    return model

# Create and train the neural network model
nn_model = create_neural_network()
history = nn_model.fit(
    [X_train_text_embedded, X_train_num], y_train,
    epochs=50, batch_size=32, validation_split=0.1,
    callbacks=[tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)]
)

# Generate predictions from the neural network model
nn_train_preds = nn_model.predict([X_train_text_embedded, X_train_num]).flatten()
nn_test_preds = nn_model.predict([X_test_text_embedded, X_test_num]).flatten()

from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
# Step 2: Train the Primary RandomForestRegressor on Numeric Features Only
rf_model_primary = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf_model_primary.fit(X_train_num, y_train)

# Generate predictions from the primary random forest model
rf_train_preds_primary = rf_model_primary.predict(X_train_num)
rf_test_preds_primary = rf_model_primary.predict(X_test_num)

# Step 3: Train a Second RandomForestRegressor as the Meta-Learner
# Combine predictions from the neural network and primary random forest as inputs for the meta-learner
train_meta_features = np.column_stack((nn_train_preds, rf_train_preds_primary))
test_meta_features = np.column_stack((nn_test_preds, rf_test_preds_primary))

# Train the meta-learner (another RandomForestRegressor) on the stacked predictions
rf_model_meta = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
rf_model_meta.fit(train_meta_features, y_train)

# Generate final predictions from the meta-learner
final_train_preds = rf_model_meta.predict(train_meta_features)
final_test_preds = rf_model_meta.predict(test_meta_features)

# Calculate R^2 Score for the Ensemble Model with RandomForest as Meta-Learner
r2_score_ensemble = r2_score(y_test, final_test_preds)
print("Ensemble Model with RandomForest as Meta-Learner R^2 Score:", r2_score_ensemble)

import pandas as pd
import tensorflow as tf
import tensorflow_hub as hub
import autokeras as ak
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
import numpy as np

# Load BERT layer for embedding
bert_layer = hub.KerasLayer("https://tfhub.dev/google/universal-sentence-encoder/4", trainable=False)

# Load and preprocess dataset
data = pd.read_csv('/content/Sample_dataset_for training.csv')
data['Tokenized_Resume'] = data['Tokenized_Resume'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Description'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Description'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Title'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Title'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Skills'] = data['Tokenized_Skills'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Experience'] = data['Experience'].fillna(0)
data['Resume_Score'] = data['Resume_Score'].fillna(data['Resume_Score'].mean())

# Combine primary text fields for embeddings
X_main_text = data['Tokenized_Resume'] + " " + data['Tokenized_Job_Description']
X_numeric = data[['Experience']]
y = data['Resume_Score'].to_numpy()

# Scale numeric features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_numeric_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_numeric)

# Split data
X_train_text, X_test_text, X_train_num, X_test_num, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_main_text, X_numeric_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42
)

# Convert text data to BERT embeddings
def embed_text(texts):
    embeddings = bert_layer(tf.convert_to_tensor(texts))
    return embeddings.numpy()

X_train_text_embedded = embed_text(X_train_text.tolist())
X_test_text_embedded = embed_text(X_test_text.tolist())

# Prepare data for AutoKeras
X_train_dict = {'text_input': X_train_text_embedded, 'numeric_input': X_train_num}
X_test_dict = {'text_input': X_test_text_embedded, 'numeric_input': X_test_num}

# Define AutoKeras model with multiple inputs
input_text = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_text_embedded.shape[1],), name='text_input')
input_numeric = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_input')

# Create AutoKeras model to search for best architecture
auto_model = ak.AutoModel(
    inputs=[input_text, input_numeric],
    outputs=ak.RegressionHead(),
    max_trials=20,  # Adjust max_trials based on computational resources
    overwrite=True
)

# Train the AutoKeras model
auto_model.fit(X_train_dict, y_train, epochs=20, validation_split=0.1)

# Predict with AutoKeras model and evaluate
y_pred_autokeras = auto_model.predict(X_test_dict).flatten()
r2_score_autokeras = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_autokeras)
print("AutoKeras Model R^2 Score:", r2_score_autokeras)

# Load and preprocess dataset
data = pd.read_csv('/content/Sample_dataset_for training.csv')
data['Tokenized_Resume'] = data['Tokenized_Resume'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Description'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Description'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Title'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Title'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Skills'] = data['Tokenized_Skills'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Experience'] = data['Experience'].fillna(0)
data['Resume_Score'] = data['Resume_Score'].fillna(data['Resume_Score'].mean())

# Combine primary text fields for embeddings
X_main_text = data['Tokenized_Resume'] + " " + data['Tokenized_Job_Description']
X_numeric = data[['Experience']]
y = data['Resume_Score'].to_numpy()

# Scale numeric features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_numeric_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_numeric)

# Split data
X_train_text, X_test_text, X_train_num, X_test_num, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_main_text, X_numeric_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42
)

# Convert text data to BERT embeddings
def embed_text(texts):
    embeddings = bert_layer(tf.convert_to_tensor(texts))
    return embeddings.numpy()

X_train_text_embedded = embed_text(X_train_text.tolist())
X_test_text_embedded = embed_text(X_test_text.tolist())

# Prepare data for AutoKeras
X_train_dict = {'text_input': X_train_text_embedded, 'numeric_input': X_train_num}
X_test_dict = {'text_input': X_test_text_embedded, 'numeric_input': X_test_num}

# Define AutoKeras model with multiple inputs
input_text = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_text_embedded.shape[1],), name='text_input')
input_numeric = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_input')

# Create AutoKeras model to search for best architecture
auto_model = ak.AutoModel(
    inputs=[input_text, input_numeric],
    outputs=ak.RegressionHead(),
    max_trials=30,  # Adjust max_trials based on computational resources
    overwrite=True
)

# Train the AutoKeras model
auto_model.fit(X_train_dict, y_train, epochs=50, validation_split=0.05)

# Predict with AutoKeras model and evaluate
y_pred_autokeras = auto_model.predict(X_test_dict).flatten()
r2_score_autokeras = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_autokeras)
print("AutoKeras Model R^2 Score:", r2_score_autokeras)

import pandas as pd
import tensorflow as tf
import tensorflow_hub as hub
import autokeras as ak
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Input, Dense, Dropout, BatchNormalization, Concatenate
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from keras_tuner.tuners import RandomSearch
import numpy as np

# Load BERT layer for embedding
bert_layer = hub.KerasLayer("https://tfhub.dev/google/universal-sentence-encoder/4", trainable=False)

# Load and preprocess dataset
data = pd.read_csv('/content/Sample_dataset_for training.csv')
data['Tokenized_Resume'] = data['Tokenized_Resume'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Description'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Description'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Job_Title'] = data['Tokenized_Job_Title'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Tokenized_Skills'] = data['Tokenized_Skills'].fillna("").astype(str)
data['Experience'] = data['Experience'].fillna(0)
data['Resume_Score'] = data['Resume_Score'].fillna(data['Resume_Score'].mean())

# Combine primary text fields for embeddings
X_main_text = data['Tokenized_Resume'] + " " + data['Tokenized_Job_Description']
X_numeric = data[['Experience']]
y = data['Resume_Score'].to_numpy()

# Scale numeric features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_numeric_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_numeric)

# Split data
X_train_text, X_test_text, X_train_num, X_test_num, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X_main_text, X_numeric_scaled, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42
)

# Convert text data to BERT embeddings
def embed_text(texts):
    embeddings = bert_layer(tf.convert_to_tensor(texts))
    return embeddings.numpy()

X_train_text_embedded = embed_text(X_train_text.tolist())
X_test_text_embedded = embed_text(X_test_text.tolist())

# Prepare data for AutoKeras
X_train_dict = {'text_input': X_train_text_embedded, 'numeric_input': X_train_num}
X_test_dict = {'text_input': X_test_text_embedded, 'numeric_input': X_test_num}

# Define AutoKeras model
input_text = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_text_embedded.shape[1],), name='text_input')
input_numeric = ak.Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_input')

# AutoKeras Model Search
auto_model = ak.AutoModel(
    inputs=[input_text, input_numeric],
    outputs=ak.RegressionHead(),
    max_trials=20,  # Adjust max_trials based on computational resources
    overwrite=True
)

# Train the AutoKeras model
auto_model.fit(X_train_dict, y_train, epochs=20, validation_split=0.05)

# Predict with AutoKeras model and evaluate
y_pred_autokeras = auto_model.predict(X_test_dict).flatten()
r2_score_autokeras = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_autokeras)
print("AutoKeras Model R^2 Score:", r2_score_autokeras)

# Extract best model from AutoKeras for further tuning
best_model = auto_model.export_model()

def shap_model_predict(inputs):
    # Split the combined input into text and numeric parts
    texts = inputs[:, 0]
    numeric_data = np.array([x[1:] for x in inputs], dtype=np.float32)
    
    # Convert text to embeddings
    text_embeddings = embed_text(texts.tolist())
    
    # Create input dictionary with correct layer names
    input_data = {
        'input_layer': numeric_data,          # Ensure the numeric data is correctly assigned
        'input_layer_1': text_embeddings      # Use the correct name for text embeddings
    }
    
    # Get predictions
    predictions = best_model.predict(input_data)
    return predictions.flatten()

# Define the embed_text function to process text inputs for BERT
def embed_text(texts):
    # Ensure texts is a flat list of strings
    if isinstance(texts, np.ndarray):
        texts = texts.flatten().tolist()
    elif isinstance(texts, pd.Series):
        texts = texts.tolist()
        
    # Confirm each element in texts is a string
    texts = [str(text) for text in texts]
    
    # Pass list of strings to BERT layer and get embeddings
    embeddings = bert_layer(tf.convert_to_tensor(texts))
    return embeddings.numpy()
# Wrapper function for text prediction with LIME compatibility
def predict_for_text(texts):
    # Embed the batch of texts provided by LIME
    text_embeddings = embed_text(texts)
    
    # Repeat numeric_instance to match the number of perturbed text samples generated by LIME
    input_data = {
        'text_input': text_embeddings,    # BERT embeddings for text input
        'numeric_input': np.repeat(numeric_instance, len(texts), axis=0)  # Repeat numeric input for each perturbed text sample
    }
    
    predictions = auto_model.predict(input_data)
    return predictions.flatten().reshape(-1, 1)  # Return as 2D array for compatibility with LIME
# Wrapper function for numeric prediction with LIME compatibility
def predict_for_numeric(numeric_data):
    # Embed a fixed text input and repeat it to match the number of numeric samples
    text_embeddings = embed_text([text_instance])  # Fixed text instance embedding
    text_embeddings_repeated = np.repeat(text_embeddings, len(numeric_data), axis=0)  # Repeat for each perturbed numeric input
    
    # Combine repeated text embeddings with the numeric inputs
    input_data = {
        'text_input': text_embeddings_repeated,   # Repeated text embedding
        'numeric_input': numeric_data             # Varying numeric input
    }
    
    predictions = auto_model.predict(input_data)
    return predictions.flatten().reshape(-1, 1)  # Return as 2D array for compatibility with LIME

import lime
from lime import lime_tabular, lime_text
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
from collections import defaultdict

# Define the embed_text function to process text inputs for BERT
def embed_text(texts):
    if isinstance(texts, np.ndarray):
        texts = texts.flatten().tolist()
    elif isinstance(texts, pd.Series):
        texts = texts.tolist()
        
    texts = [str(text) for text in texts]
    embeddings = bert_layer(tf.convert_to_tensor(texts))
    return embeddings.numpy()

# Wrapper function for text prediction
def predict_for_text(texts):
    text_embeddings = embed_text(texts)
    input_data = {
        'text_input': text_embeddings,
        'numeric_input': np.repeat(numeric_instance, len(texts), axis=0)
    }
    predictions = auto_model.predict(input_data)
    return predictions.flatten().reshape(-1, 1)

# Wrapper function for numeric prediction
def predict_for_numeric(numeric_data):
    text_embeddings = embed_text([text_instance])
    text_embeddings_repeated = np.repeat(text_embeddings, len(numeric_data), axis=0)
    input_data = {
        'text_input': text_embeddings_repeated,
        'numeric_input': numeric_data
    }
    predictions = auto_model.predict(input_data)
    return predictions.flatten().reshape(-1, 1)

# Function to calculate global explanation
def global_lime_explanation(num_samples=10):
    lime_text_explainer = lime_text.LimeTextExplainer(class_names=["Resume_Score"])
    lime_numeric_explainer = lime_tabular.LimeTabularExplainer(
        X_train_num,
        feature_names=['Experience'],
        mode='regression'
    )
    
    # Initialize dictionary to store aggregated feature importance
    global_importance_text = defaultdict(float)
    global_importance_numeric = defaultdict(float)
    
    # Iterate over multiple samples to get global feature importance
    for i in range(num_samples):
        text_instance = X_test_text.iloc[i]
        numeric_instance = X_test_num[i].reshape(1, -1)

        # Get LIME explanation for text
        text_exp = lime_text_explainer.explain_instance(
            text_instance,
            predict_for_text,
            num_features=10,
            labels=[0]
        )
        
        # Aggregate text feature importance
        for feature, importance in text_exp.as_list(label=0):
            global_importance_text[feature] += importance

        # Get LIME explanation for numeric features
        numeric_exp = lime_numeric_explainer.explain_instance(
            numeric_instance[0],
            predict_for_numeric,
            num_features=1,
            labels=[0]
        )
        
        # Aggregate numeric feature importance
        for feature, importance in numeric_exp.as_list(label=0):
            global_importance_numeric[feature] += importance

    # Convert to DataFrames for easy viewing and averaging
    global_text_df = pd.DataFrame(list(global_importance_text.items()), columns=['Feature', 'Importance'])
    global_text_df['Importance'] /= num_samples  # Average importance across samples

    global_numeric_df = pd.DataFrame(list(global_importance_numeric.items()), columns=['Feature', 'Importance'])
    global_numeric_df['Importance'] /= num_samples  # Average importance across samples
    
    return global_text_df, global_numeric_df

# Run global LIME explanation
global_text_importance, global_numeric_importance = global_lime_explanation(num_samples=10)

# Display the global feature importance
print("Global Text Feature Importance:")
print(global_text_importance)

print("\nGlobal Numeric Feature Importance:")
print(global_numeric_importance)

# Define a model-building function for Keras Tuner
def build_model(hp):
    # Hyperparameters for tuning
    dense_units = hp.Int('dense_units', min_value=64, max_value=512, step=64)
    dropout_rate = hp.Float('dropout_rate', min_value=0.2, max_value=0.6, step=0.1)
    learning_rate = hp.Float('learning_rate', min_value=1e-5, max_value=1e-2, sampling='log')

    # Define inputs
    input_text = Input(shape=(X_train_text_embedded.shape[1],), name='text_input')
    input_numeric = Input(shape=(X_train_num.shape[1],), name='numeric_input')

    # Reshape text input and apply GlobalAveragePooling
    text_branch = Reshape((X_train_text_embedded.shape[1], 1))(input_text)
    text_branch = GlobalAveragePooling1D()(text_branch)

    # Define text branch
    text_branch = Dense(dense_units, activation='relu')(text_branch)
    text_branch = BatchNormalization()(text_branch)
    text_branch = Dropout(dropout_rate)(text_branch)

    # Define numeric branch
    numeric_branch = Dense(dense_units // 2, activation='relu')(input_numeric)
    numeric_branch = BatchNormalization()(numeric_branch)
    numeric_branch = Dropout(dropout_rate)(numeric_branch)

    # Combine branches
    combined = Concatenate()([text_branch, numeric_branch])
    combined = Dense(dense_units, activation='relu')(combined)
    combined = BatchNormalization()(combined)
    combined = Dropout(dropout_rate)(combined)
    output = Dense(1)(combined)

    # Compile the model with fresh optimizer to avoid warnings
    model = Model(inputs=[input_text, input_numeric], outputs=output)
    model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate), loss='mse', metrics=['mse'])
    return model

# Initialize Keras Tuner with RandomSearch
tuner = RandomSearch(
    build_model,
    objective='val_loss',
    max_trials=10,  # Adjust max_trials for more extensive search
    executions_per_trial=1,
    directory='kt_dir',
    project_name='resume_score_tuning'
)

# Run the tuner search on training data
tuner.search(X_train_dict, y_train, epochs=10, validation_split=0.1)

# Retrieve the best model from Keras Tuner
best_tuned_model = tuner.get_best_models(num_models=1)[0]

# Evaluate the best tuned model
y_pred_tuned = best_tuned_model.predict(X_test_dict).flatten()
r2_score_tuned = r2_score(y_test, y_pred_tuned)
print("Tuned Model R^2 Score:", r2_score_tuned)
